We now explore the interesting features of the graphs of quadratics. In addition to intercepts, quadratics have an interesting feature where they change direction, called the vertex . You probably noticed that all quadratics are related to transformations of the basic quadratic function \(f(x)=x^{2}\). Notice that the horizontal and vertical shifts of the basic quadratic determine the location of the vertex of the parabola; the vertex is unaffected by stretches and compressions. Exercise \(\PageIndex{1}\) A coordinate grid has been superimposed over the quadratic path of a basketball(From http://blog.mrmeyer.com/?p=4778 , © Dan Meyer, CC-BY). Find an equation for the path of the ball. Does he make the basket? The path passes through the origin with vertex at (-4, 7). \[h(x) = -\dfrac{7}{16}(x + 4)^2 + 7
onumber\] To make the shot, \(h(-7.5)\) would need to be about 4. \(h(-7.5) \approx 1.64\); he doesn't make it. forms of quadratic function The standard form of a quadratic function is \[f(x)=ax^{2} +bx+c \label{standard}\] The transformation form of a quadratic function is \[f(x)=a(x-h)^{2} +k \label{trans}\] The vertex of the quadratic function is located at (\(h\), \(k\)), where \(h\) and \(k\) are the numbers in the transformation form of the function. Because the vertex appears in the transformation form, it is often called the vertex form . In the previous example, we saw that it is possible to rewrite a quadratic function given in transformation form and rewrite it in standard form by expanding the formula. It would be useful to reverse this process since the transformation form reveals the vertex. Expanding out the general transformation form of a quadratic gives: \[ egin{array}{l} {f(x)=a(x-h)^{2} +k=a(x-h)(x-h)+k} \ {f(x)=a(x^{2} -2xh+h^{2} )+k=ax^{2} -2ahx+ah^{2} +k} \end{array}
onumber \] This should be equal to the standard form of the quadratic: \[ax^{2} -2ahx+ah^{2} +k=ax^{2} +bx+c
onumber \] The second degree terms are already equal. For the linear terms to be equal, the coefficients must be equal: \[-2ah=b	ext{ ,so }h=-\dfrac{b}{2a}
onumber\] This provides us a method to determine the horizontal shift of the quadratic from the standard form. We could likewise set the constant terms equal to find: \[ah^{2} +k=c	ext{ ,so }k=c-ah^{2} =c-a\left(-\dfrac{b}{2a} ight)^{2} =c-a\dfrac{b^{2} }{4a^{2} } =c-\dfrac{b^{2} }{4a}
onumber \] In practice, though, it is usually easier to remember that \(k\) is the output value of the function when the input is \(h\), so \(k=f(h)\). finding the vertex of a quadratic For a quadratic given in standard form, the vertex (\(h\), \(k\)) is located at: \[h=-\dfrac{b}{2a} , k=f(h)=f\left(\dfrac{-b}{2a} ight)\] Exercise \(\PageIndex{2}\) Given the equation \(g(x)=13+x^{2} -6x\) write the equation in standard form and then in transformation/vertex form. \(g(x) = x^2 - 6x + 13\) in Standard form (Equation ef{standard} Finding the vertex, \(h = \dfrac{-(-6)}{2(1)} = 3\). \[k = g(3) = 3^2 - 6(3) + 13 = 4
onumber \] \(g(x) = (x - 3)^2 + 4\) in Transformation form (Equation ef{trans}) As an alternative to using a formula for finding the vertex, the equation can also be written into vertex form by completing the square . This process is most easily explained through example. In most cases, using the formula for finding the vertex will be quicker and easier than completing the square, but completing the square is a useful technique when faced with some other algebraic problems. In addition to enabling us to more easily graph a quadratic written in standard form, finding the vertex serves another important purpose – it allows us to determine the maximum or minimum value of the function, depending on which way the graph opens.

