Example \(\PageIndex{6}\) Find all the real and complex zeros of \(f(x)=12x^{5} -20x^{4} +19x^{3} -6x^{2} -2x+1\). Solution Using the Rational Roots Theorem, the possible real rational roots are \[\left\{\pm \dfrac{1}{1} ,\pm \dfrac{1}{2} ,\pm \dfrac{1}{3} ,\pm \dfrac{1}{4} ,\pm \dfrac{1}{6} ,\pm \dfrac{1}{12} ight\}
onumber \] Testing \(\dfrac{1}{2}\), Success! Because the graph bounces at this intercept, it is likely that this zero has multiplicity 2. We can try synthetic division again to test that. The other real root appears to be \(-\dfrac{1}{3}\) or \(-\dfrac{1}{4}\). Testing \(-\dfrac{1}{3}\), Excellent! So far, we have factored the polynomial to \[f(x)=\left(x-\dfrac{1}{2} ight)^{2} \left(x+\dfrac{1}{3} ight)\left(12x^{2} -12x+12ight)=12\left(x-\dfrac{1}{2} ight)^{2} \left(x+\dfrac{1}{3} ight)\left(x^{2} -x+1ight)
onumber \] We can use the quadratic formula to find the two remaining zeros by setting \(x^{2} -x+1=0\), which are likely complex zeros. \[x=\dfrac{1\pm \sqrt{(-1)^{2} -4(1)(1)} }{2(1)} =\dfrac{1\pm \sqrt{-3} }{2} =\dfrac{1\pm i\sqrt{3} }{2} 
onumber \] The zeros of the function are \(x=\dfrac{1}{2} ,-\dfrac{1}{3} ,\dfrac{1+i\sqrt{3} }{2} ,\dfrac{1-i\sqrt{3} }{2}\). We could write the function fully factored as \(f(x)=12\left(x-\dfrac{1}{2} ight)^{2} \left(x+\dfrac{1}{3} ight)\left(x-\dfrac{1+i\sqrt{3} }{2} ight)\left(x-\dfrac{1-i\sqrt{3} }{2} ight)\).

Example \(\PageIndex{11}\) Find the intercepts of \(f(x)=\dfrac{(x-2)(x+3)}{(x-1)(x+2)(x-5)}\) Solution We can find the vertical intercept by evaluating the function at zero \[f(0)=\dfrac{(0-2)(0+3)}{(0-1)(0+2)(0-5)} =\dfrac{-6}{10} =-\dfrac{3}{5}
onumber \] The horizontal intercepts will occur when the function is equal to zero: \[0=\dfrac{(x-2)(x+3)}{(x-1)(x+2)(x-5)}
onumber \] This is zero when the numerator is zero \[ egin{array}{l} {0=(x-2)(x+3)} \ {x=2,\; -3} \end{array}
onumber \]

